00:09:11.252 --> 00:09:13.460
finds it in the app store
and shows someone, and then

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:14.704
just goes from there.

00:09:14.704 --> 00:09:16.620
There's definitely been
some press we've done.

00:09:16.620 --> 00:09:17.994
When we rolled
out international,

00:09:17.994 --> 00:09:21.950
we went to Netherlands and some
places that are-- Netherlands,

00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:23.960
93% of people are
connected internet.

00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:25.420
It's huge.

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:27.650
And so these are
great, and they're

00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:28.780
amazing social networks.

00:09:28.780 --> 00:09:31.800
Brazil, Netherlands they're
like first adopters.

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:34.381
And so we went there, put
out some little press things,

00:09:34.381 --> 00:09:35.380
get some people into it.

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:37.546
And then the rest has to
take care of itself, right.

00:09:37.546 --> 00:09:39.910
And so that's kind of
been our strategy so far.

00:09:39.910 --> 00:09:42.170
The next step for us is
to break a little bit out

00:09:42.170 --> 00:09:45.860
of tech and more into
lifestyle and more

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:47.990
of a mainstream audience
and see how they do.

00:09:47.990 --> 00:09:50.470
But again, timing is everything.

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:54.570
And we need to make sure
we're not going too fast, not

00:09:54.570 --> 00:09:58.962
too far, and kind of growing
at a very steady, solid rate.

00:09:58.962 --> 00:10:00.670
MALE SPEAKER 1: So
let's talk about that.

00:10:00.670 --> 00:10:02.882
How do you move
into the mainstream?

00:10:02.882 --> 00:10:04.465
Because I think some
of these startups

00:10:04.465 --> 00:10:05.770
see that tech crunch bump.

00:10:05.770 --> 00:10:08.460
They see press come in,
lots of initial users.

00:10:08.460 --> 00:10:09.377
People get excited.

00:10:09.377 --> 00:10:11.960
And then two months later, you
don't hear about those startups

00:10:11.960 --> 00:10:12.180
again.

00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:14.320
How are you-- what are
you doing to avoid that?

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:18.510
DAVID: I think right now for us,
it's a game of show and tell.

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:21.740
It's always showing
the kind of content

00:10:21.740 --> 00:10:23.240
that's created on
Secret, whether we

00:10:23.240 --> 00:10:26.847
are kind of collecting secrets
and showing it to people,

00:10:26.847 --> 00:10:28.680
and showing them this
is the kind of content

00:10:28.680 --> 00:10:30.320
you can find on Secret.

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:34.430
That way people in the
Midwest or wherever,

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:36.590
they see things
that relate to them.

00:10:36.590 --> 00:10:39.660
That's I think
the real key, when

00:10:39.660 --> 00:10:42.410
everyone-- the goal is
whenever anyone signs up

00:10:42.410 --> 00:10:44.530
to Secret, the first
few secrets they see

00:10:44.530 --> 00:10:46.780
should be something
relatable, something close by,

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:49.689
something in their campus,
something they're interested,

00:10:49.689 --> 00:10:50.480
that kind of thing.

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:52.979
And they need to make that deep
connection with the product.

00:10:52.979 --> 00:10:55.490
And that kind of
content is what helps

00:10:55.490 --> 00:10:58.430
people, especially mainstream,
kind of connect with it

00:10:58.430 --> 00:10:59.560
and want to use it.

00:10:59.560 --> 00:11:00.395
MALE SPEAKER 1: So it
seems like your development

00:11:00.395 --> 00:11:02.096
and your distribution
go hand in hand.

00:11:02.096 --> 00:11:03.470
When the user
comes on, they want

00:11:03.470 --> 00:11:06.580
to see content that's compelling
that keeps them coming back.

00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:09.640
How do you make sure that those
first three posts are most

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:10.140
engaging?

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:10.848
Is it algorithms?

00:11:10.848 --> 00:11:12.290
What are you doing to make that?

00:11:12.290 --> 00:11:13.120
DAVID: So there's a few things.

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:14.495
I mean, we have
a moderation team

00:11:14.495 --> 00:11:16.550
that's always curating
some of the best content.

00:11:16.550 --> 00:11:20.120
They are going through stuff and
finding it and kind of picking

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:22.670
out things, so that
when people do come on,

00:11:22.670 --> 00:11:25.040
that they see that kind
of stuff to kind of set

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:27.770
the pace and the tone
for what the product is.

00:11:27.770 --> 00:11:30.162
I fully, fully believe
the beauty begets beauty.

00:11:30.162 --> 00:11:31.620
What they see is
what they're going

00:11:31.620 --> 00:11:34.420
to want to mimic and represent.

00:11:34.420 --> 00:11:36.330
And that goes back
to the original point

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:37.872
of battling negativity.

00:11:37.872 --> 00:11:40.080
If you join and you see
something extremely negative,

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:41.454
you see something
that's hurtful,

00:11:41.454 --> 00:11:44.662
or see something
that's like whatever,

00:11:44.662 --> 00:11:46.120
not safe for work,
stuff like that.

00:11:46.120 --> 00:11:47.800
You're like what is this?

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:49.220
What's going on?

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:51.605
You kind of want to help steer
people in that direction.

00:11:51.605 --> 00:11:54.340
And that first experience
is the most important.

00:11:54.340 --> 00:11:56.001
The best experience,
of course, is

00:11:56.001 --> 00:11:57.500
when they join and
they're instantly

00:11:57.500 --> 00:11:58.830
connected to their friends.

00:11:58.830 --> 00:12:01.121
And they have something that's
like this from a friend.

00:12:01.121 --> 00:12:04.650
It's like someone says
even the simplest things.

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:06.000
Someone says like, romance me.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:06.958
And it's from a friend.

00:12:06.958 --> 00:12:09.730
You're like, is
this someone I know.

00:12:09.730 --> 00:12:09.960
MALE SPEAKER 1: That
would make my day.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:11.168
DAVID: Is this my girlfriend.

00:12:11.168 --> 00:12:12.440
Is this-- yeah, exactly.

00:12:12.440 --> 00:12:14.190
And you connect with
it on a deeper level,

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:16.170
rather than you go
to some other product

00:12:16.170 --> 00:12:17.420
where it's just a public feed.

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:18.350
And it's random people.

00:12:18.350 --> 00:12:19.350
You're like, romance me.

00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:21.180
Whatever, I don't
care about that.

00:12:21.180 --> 00:12:21.720
MALE SPEAKER 1: So
take me through.

00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:23.345
When was the moment
when you were first

00:12:23.345 --> 00:12:25.480
building the product where
it resonated with you.

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:28.100
When you're like, wow, I think
this could be something as big

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:30.160
as we see today with
what Secret has become.

00:12:30.160 --> 00:12:31.590
When did that happen for you?

00:12:31.590 --> 00:12:34.006
DAVID: So I remember when we're
testing with our friends--

00:12:34.006 --> 00:12:36.440
again, we only had about
250 people on the platform.

00:12:36.440 --> 00:12:39.310
It was a little bit
before Christmas.

00:12:39.310 --> 00:12:41.870
And someone had
posted and said, I'm

00:12:41.870 --> 00:12:46.690
thinking of asking my girlfriend
to marry her-- or marry me

00:12:46.690 --> 00:12:49.010
on Christmas Day.

00:12:49.010 --> 00:12:50.592
Is that poor form?

00:12:50.592 --> 00:12:51.550
What do you guys think?

00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:54.540
All these people, my friends
and my co-founders' friends,

00:12:54.540 --> 00:12:57.500
is the intersection
of all of us,

00:12:57.500 --> 00:12:59.979
we're giving feedback
and talking about it.

00:12:59.979 --> 00:13:01.770
And I was like, this
is really interesting.

00:13:01.770 --> 00:13:05.240
I wonder if she's going to find
out what's going to happen.

00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:08.580
Then a little bit after
Christmas, my friend, Rich,

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:12.130
had posted on Facebook a picture
of the ring, just got engaged.

00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:13.669
It was kind of like a reveal.

00:13:13.669 --> 00:13:15.085
And that got me
thinking like, you

00:13:15.085 --> 00:13:17.710
know what, there's this
new class of communication.

00:13:17.710 --> 00:13:19.570
The things we think
and feel, things we

00:13:19.570 --> 00:13:20.486
want to put out there.

00:13:20.486 --> 00:13:22.420
Or we just say in private
like a dinner table,

00:13:22.420 --> 00:13:26.400
that you can't really put
out there and feel and get

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:27.990
your friends to
respond to, right.

00:13:27.990 --> 00:13:29.530
It's that other
side of the story.

00:13:29.530 --> 00:13:33.252
And that's what I knew that we
had something, because I fully

00:13:33.252 --> 00:13:34.960
believe, especially
with social networks,

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:36.870
you look at new
apps like Slingshot.

00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:38.860
Or you look at all
these new things.

00:13:38.860 --> 00:13:42.680
It has to create kind of,
a new type of content,

00:13:42.680 --> 00:13:43.940
a new class of communication.

00:13:43.940 --> 00:13:46.260
You can't just build another
Instagram and build it better.

00:13:46.260 --> 00:13:47.600
Because we're all on Instagram.

00:13:47.600 --> 00:13:50.180
Why is this is going-- so
you've always got to find those

00:13:50.180 --> 00:13:51.840
new places, those
new things, where

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:54.300
people have to have a new
way to express themselves.

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.570
And something that
resonates with everyone.

00:13:56.570 --> 00:13:59.029
And so that's when I kind of
like knew something was there.

00:13:59.029 --> 00:14:00.153
MALE SPEAKER 1: Absolutely.

00:14:00.153 --> 00:14:02.180
And tell me, give me a
glimpses into the future.

00:14:02.180 --> 00:14:03.470
What's coming up for Secret?

00:14:03.470 --> 00:14:06.720
I know you guys are having a
lot of exciting developments

00:14:06.720 --> 00:14:10.190
to the product and adding
more experiences for users,

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:11.290
so it even more resonates.

00:14:11.290 --> 00:14:13.760
What are you doing with Secret
to allow the distribution

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:14.770
to only grow?

00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:17.860
DAVID: Yeah, so I think the
most important thing any product

00:14:17.860 --> 00:14:19.640
that once you hit
product market fit,

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:22.295
or you feel like you've hit
it, you need to constantly

00:14:22.295 --> 00:14:25.520
be tightening the bolts and
making sure that the product is

00:14:25.520 --> 00:14:28.247
robust and strong, and
things aren't falling off.

00:14:28.247 --> 00:14:29.330
You're not missing things.

00:14:29.330 --> 00:14:30.460
You're not losing things.

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:33.000
You take a product
like again, Snapchat.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:33.790
I love Snapchat.

00:14:33.790 --> 00:14:35.410
I love how they've grown.

00:14:35.410 --> 00:14:38.130
The first year, they
were slowly growing.

00:14:38.130 --> 00:14:40.090
They were not, it was
not an overnight thing.

00:14:40.090 --> 00:14:43.117
It took Twitter a very,
very long time, right.

00:14:43.117 --> 00:14:44.075
These things take time.

00:14:44.075 --> 00:14:47.090
And you just have to build up
that core and strengthen it.

00:14:47.090 --> 00:14:50.300
And eventually, you
never when it resonates

00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:51.755
and it goes
mainstream like that.

00:14:51.755 --> 00:14:54.130
So number one is we're just
constantly always making sure

00:14:54.130 --> 00:14:56.500
that push notifications
work, everything works,

00:14:56.500 --> 00:14:58.640
people are getting quality
stuff in the stream.

00:14:58.640 --> 00:14:59.970
The core is there.

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:02.260
Then we start looking at
other things like well,

00:15:02.260 --> 00:15:03.710
we see what our users are doing.

00:15:03.710 --> 00:15:04.910
They want to message each other.

00:15:04.910 --> 00:15:07.285
They want to have these private
little conversations when

00:15:07.285 --> 00:15:08.950
they connect in a
normal conversation.

00:15:08.950 --> 00:15:11.550
So should we build a
direct messaging product.

00:15:11.550 --> 00:15:13.120
And of course we
want to do that.

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:15.280
But like I said,
timing is everything.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:17.520
And it needs to make sense.

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:19.550
And everything
you-- every time you

00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:20.970
add a new feature
to your product,

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:22.053
it's kind of like a story.

00:15:22.053 --> 00:15:24.820
You have to go back to the
beginning and reread that story

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:27.570
and make sure it makes
sense cohesively.

00:15:27.570 --> 00:15:31.100
And so with that, I think direct
messaging is really, really

00:15:31.100 --> 00:15:32.610
important.

00:15:32.610 --> 00:15:34.880
And again, just
showing more content.

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:41.520
There's so-- I can't stress
enough how much good stuff

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:44.237
there is on our product
that a lot of people do see.

00:15:44.237 --> 00:15:45.320
But a lot of people don't.

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:47.750
And we want to be able
to show some of that

00:15:47.750 --> 00:15:50.204
and have our users
really be proud of things

00:15:50.204 --> 00:15:50.870
they've created.

00:15:50.870 --> 00:15:52.369
Maybe they don't
take credit for it,

00:15:52.369 --> 00:15:54.720
like this was mine
of course, but just

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:56.910
show some of that really,
really good stuff.

00:15:56.910 --> 00:15:58.890
And I think that's
really important, too.

00:15:58.890 --> 00:16:00.150
MALE SPEAKER 1: So for me,
you mentioned that last one.

00:16:00.150 --> 00:16:01.800
It really stuck out
for me, not taking

00:16:01.800 --> 00:16:03.216
credit for what
you put out there.

00:16:03.216 --> 00:16:05.180
Because I think like
on Facebook, Twitter,

00:16:05.180 --> 00:16:08.419
so many of us just think about
wow, it's got so many likes,

00:16:08.419 --> 00:16:09.210
it's got favorites.

00:16:09.210 --> 00:16:09.959
It got re-tweeted.

00:16:09.959 --> 00:16:13.680
But on your network,
none of that matters.

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:15.340
But people still
keep coming back.

00:16:15.340 --> 00:16:16.200
Why?

00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:20.540
DAVID: Well, so everyone
loves that sense or connecting

00:16:20.540 --> 00:16:21.140
with others.

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:22.690
And in the heart,
or like, whatever's

00:16:22.690 --> 00:16:25.191
the light weight
feeling that someone--

00:16:25.191 --> 00:16:26.940
I connected with someone
out there, right.

00:16:26.940 --> 00:16:28.940
There's someone out there
that liked what I did.

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:30.148
And that's just, it's a drug.

00:16:30.148 --> 00:16:30.950
It's addictive.

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:31.970
And people love that.

00:16:31.970 --> 00:16:34.440
But I will say this what's
the funniest thing to me

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:37.520
is when people do take
credit for their secrets.

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:40.490
They will literally post them on
Twitter, post them on Facebook,

00:16:40.490 --> 00:16:41.580
and say, oh man.

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:43.600
I got 2000 likes on this.

00:16:43.600 --> 00:16:46.310
They'll come back a month later
and say, it's at 3,000 likes.

00:16:46.310 --> 00:16:47.210
And there's two things there.

00:16:47.210 --> 00:16:48.825
With Secret, because
things continue

00:16:48.825 --> 00:16:51.970
to spread through networks,
the half life of a given secret

00:16:51.970 --> 00:16:53.999
can be weeks, if not months.

00:16:53.999 --> 00:16:56.290
So if someone posts something,
and it just keeps going.

00:16:56.290 --> 00:16:58.302
As new people come on,
they see this secret.

00:16:58.302 --> 00:16:59.010
And they like it.

00:16:59.010 --> 00:17:00.654
And they do it.

00:17:00.654 --> 00:17:02.320
But yeah, my mom does
