extremely to a fault.

00:18:45.090 --> 00:18:50.080
And I think in the early days,
I had this idea for the ability

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:51.890
to send these
anonymous love notes,

00:18:51.890 --> 00:18:55.930
love-- it was very personal to
me, right, to my girlfriend.

00:18:55.930 --> 00:18:58.290
And I'm like, I want
to be able to tell her

00:18:58.290 --> 00:19:00.720
I love her without her
knowing it's from me,

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:03.424
just focus on the words,
kind of like digital flowers.

00:19:03.424 --> 00:19:04.840
And this just meant
so much to me.

00:19:04.840 --> 00:19:07.975
And I remember I showed
my now co-founder, Chris.

00:19:07.975 --> 00:19:08.640
I'm like, hey.

00:19:08.640 --> 00:19:09.840
I'm working on this thing.

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:11.000
Let's do it.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:15.160
And in the very first, I guess,
two months of our building

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:18.270
this, he was always pushing me.

00:19:18.270 --> 00:19:20.637
Dude, I think we
need to-- there's

00:19:20.637 --> 00:19:21.720
going to be bullying here.

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:23.640
There's going to be issues.

00:19:23.640 --> 00:19:27.070
We've got to try
something else, again,

00:19:27.070 --> 00:19:28.400
the broadcast model, whatever.

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:31.640
And it was a good month where
I was just like holding strong,

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:33.620
no we have to do it this way.

00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:34.830
This is what I want.

00:19:34.830 --> 00:19:37.200
And eventually it
took a few things,

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:40.050
but mostly it took Apple
basically coming down on us

00:19:40.050 --> 00:19:42.420
and saying, nope, you
can't send anonymous SMS.

00:19:42.420 --> 00:19:44.880
That was the-- we
couldn't do it.

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:46.350
We switched and pivoted.

00:19:46.350 --> 00:19:49.670
And immediately, our friends
started using it more.

00:19:49.670 --> 00:19:51.970
It was something
we were proud of.

00:19:51.970 --> 00:19:54.090
And I think the biggest
thing there was just

00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:56.840
I was far too stubborn
with my own idea

00:19:56.840 --> 00:19:59.129
and what I wanted
to do at that time.

00:19:59.129 --> 00:20:01.670
Because I'd built this little
thing, then actually letting go

00:20:01.670 --> 00:20:03.110
and trying to pivot.

00:20:03.110 --> 00:20:05.600
I think a lot of companies
make the mistake of they

00:20:05.600 --> 00:20:08.370
will hold onto an idea and
even launch it, and then

00:20:08.370 --> 00:20:09.290
be afraid to pivot.

00:20:09.290 --> 00:20:12.580
But I think that's-- you
learn a lot along the way.

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:15.170
And you need to take that
learning and change it, right.

00:20:15.170 --> 00:20:18.380
Never make the same mistakes
twice, that kind of thing.

00:20:18.380 --> 00:20:21.360
And that was a big learning
experience for me, I think.

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:22.957
Most people don't know.

00:20:22.957 --> 00:20:24.040
MALE SPEAKER 1: Fantastic.

00:20:24.040 --> 00:20:25.790
So you've supplied so
much good stuff here

00:20:25.790 --> 00:20:28.360
from sharing insights
about your early days,

00:20:28.360 --> 00:20:32.510
even telling us about your
mom's secrets on the platform.

00:20:32.510 --> 00:20:34.654
But I just want to
give you the space

00:20:34.654 --> 00:20:37.070
to talk about maybe a final
piece of advice you would give

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:39.600
to an entrepreneur or developer
who's starting from day one,

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:41.287
remembering where
were in January.

00:20:41.287 --> 00:20:43.620
And then we're going to open
up to you guys, because I'm

00:20:43.620 --> 00:20:45.860
sure you guys have a lot
of questions to ask David.

00:20:45.860 --> 00:20:48.550
And we'll pass around mic
so you guys get the chance.

00:20:48.550 --> 00:20:51.791
DAVID: Yeah, I think the
biggest thing that I've learned,

00:20:51.791 --> 00:20:53.290
so I was at Square
for a year after.

00:20:53.290 --> 00:20:55.380
I was at Google for
five years before that.

00:20:55.380 --> 00:20:58.920
Google's great at
managing complexity.

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:01.680
But that's only like
one piece of the puzzle.

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:05.452
The most important thing is
to keep it extremely simple,

00:21:05.452 --> 00:21:07.660
so you can keep the entire
product, the entire thing,

00:21:07.660 --> 00:21:08.460
in your head.

00:21:08.460 --> 00:21:09.960
Every good idea,
every good product,

00:21:09.960 --> 00:21:11.668
you should be able to
build in a weekend.

00:21:11.668 --> 00:21:13.869
Pack it together in a
weekend, you have something,

00:21:13.869 --> 00:21:14.660
and it makes sense.

00:21:14.660 --> 00:21:18.132
I mean, you look at any
really successful product

00:21:18.132 --> 00:21:20.090
and how it started, and
it started very simple.

00:21:20.090 --> 00:21:23.370
Even Google itself started
very, very, very simple.

00:21:23.370 --> 00:21:25.930
Take all these documents,
rank them in a novel way,

00:21:25.930 --> 00:21:27.990
and then you can
search them, making it

00:21:27.990 --> 00:21:30.834
just-- there's things you can
hack together very quickly.

00:21:30.834 --> 00:21:33.500
And I would say that again, when
it comes to building a product,

00:21:33.500 --> 00:21:36.530
before you launch,
simplicity is the key.

00:21:36.530 --> 00:21:38.480
Everything you add
is already some form

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:41.937
of debt, that's the
most important thing.

00:21:41.937 --> 00:21:43.020
MALE SPEAKER 1: I love it.

00:21:43.020 --> 00:21:43.520
Cool.

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:45.370
So we'll open up to
questions from you guys.

00:21:45.370 --> 00:21:48.818
And we'll pass around the mic.

00:21:48.818 --> 00:21:52.330
Yeah, we'll get you the
mic here so everyone

00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:54.069
can hear your question.

00:21:54.069 --> 00:21:55.610
AUDIENCE: Could you
talk a little bit

00:21:55.610 --> 00:22:00.220
about what your user
growth curve looks like?

00:22:00.220 --> 00:22:01.420
DAVID: Sure.

00:22:01.420 --> 00:22:04.380
So I don't have to repeat the
question since you have a mic.

00:22:04.380 --> 00:22:07.704
Our user graph curve, I think--
so first of all, obviously

00:22:07.704 --> 00:22:09.620
any product that's
growing, when you zoom out,

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:14.510
we're only five months old,
it's this nice like linear curve

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:15.290
upward.

00:22:15.290 --> 00:22:17.909
But then when you zoom in and
you look on a day to day basis,

00:22:17.909 --> 00:22:19.450
or you look week
over week, something

00:22:19.450 --> 00:22:22.600
like that, you see very--
this kind of thing.

00:22:22.600 --> 00:22:25.350
It's just on the way up,
you see really big spikes.

00:22:25.350 --> 00:22:28.820
And then it dips a little
bit, and then spike and dip.

00:22:28.820 --> 00:22:31.109
I would say right now
it is nerve racking.

00:22:31.109 --> 00:22:33.150
Every time you see like
this giant spike and then

00:22:33.150 --> 00:22:34.820
like oh, things
are slowing down.

00:22:34.820 --> 00:22:35.900
You're like, that it.

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:38.440
We're out of
business, game over.

00:22:38.440 --> 00:22:40.640
But then eventually
it picks back up.

00:22:40.640 --> 00:22:43.790
And so I think we're still
too young to really have

00:22:43.790 --> 00:22:47.800
this like nice, gradual,
exponential curve.

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:51.025
But we have microcosms of it,
which are really interesting

00:22:51.025 --> 00:22:51.775
and nerve racking.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:03.590
AUDIENCE: I didn't quite
catch the-- you started on iOS

00:23:03.590 --> 00:23:04.200
and then left.

00:23:04.200 --> 00:23:05.710
And where did you go from there?

00:23:05.710 --> 00:23:06.970
And how did that happen again?

00:23:06.970 --> 00:23:08.160
DAVID: So sorry, I started on?

00:23:08.160 --> 00:23:09.368
AUDIENCE: iOS, is that right?

00:23:09.368 --> 00:23:11.774
Because somebody said you
can't send anonymous SMS.

00:23:11.774 --> 00:23:12.440
DAVID: Oh, yeah.

00:23:12.440 --> 00:23:15.240
So we initially
built the product

00:23:15.240 --> 00:23:19.630
to send these anonymous kind
of messages, anonymous SMS,

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:22.220
where you would pick
someone in the address book,

00:23:22.220 --> 00:23:24.680
you click a button, and
then the server sends

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:26.494
anonymous message to the user.

00:23:26.494 --> 00:23:27.910
And so they get a
thing that says,

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:29.618
hey someone has shared
a secret with you.

00:23:29.618 --> 00:23:30.740
Here's the link.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:32.420
That's against
Apple's guidelines.

00:23:32.420 --> 00:23:33.990
There's rule 22.6.

00:23:33.990 --> 00:23:36.435
I remember very intimately,
which apparently I

00:23:36.435 --> 00:23:38.060
thought I read the
guidelines before we

00:23:38.060 --> 00:23:39.060
started working on this.

00:23:39.060 --> 00:23:41.320
And then I was really ashamed.

00:23:41.320 --> 00:23:44.910
But they just say you cannot
send anonymous or prank SMS.

00:23:44.910 --> 00:23:47.480
And that's really more for
carriers and things like that.

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:49.410
There are apps that do that.

00:23:49.410 --> 00:23:52.900
But once you become kind of
on the radar, whatever like,

00:23:52.900 --> 00:23:54.040
it's just not good.

00:23:54.040 --> 00:23:57.610
So that's why most products
don't do the whole,

00:23:57.610 --> 00:24:00.660
select a bunch of people and
we'll just send invites to them

00:24:00.660 --> 00:24:01.960
from the server anymore.

00:24:01.960 --> 00:24:03.800
AUDIENCE: What was your fix?

00:24:03.800 --> 00:24:05.160
DAVID: We didn't do that.

00:24:05.160 --> 00:24:08.235
We just built a new product.

00:24:08.235 --> 00:24:09.110
MALE SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:24:15.610 --> 00:24:19.320
AUDIENCE: What do you think
about upcoming competitors

00:24:19.320 --> 00:24:22.390
from different countries
in India, Germany,

00:24:22.390 --> 00:24:26.780
that came same time, so they
had the same ideas, maybe around

00:24:26.780 --> 00:24:27.460
the time.

00:24:27.460 --> 00:24:30.280
DAVID: Yeah, so
you know, I think

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:32.920
that's an entire
saga in the life,

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:35.500
in the short life of Secret.

00:24:35.500 --> 00:24:39.220
With competitors, we've
intimately had to face this.

00:24:39.220 --> 00:24:40.980
There was a clone
created of Secret,

00:24:40.980 --> 00:24:43.020
literally they exact same thing.

00:24:43.020 --> 00:24:45.250
I mean, it's weird
seeing your own product,

00:24:45.250 --> 00:24:47.370
like the exact same product.

00:24:47.370 --> 00:24:51.165
And again, it grew in Russia.

00:24:51.165 --> 00:24:54.280
But in China, this
competitor came out

00:24:54.280 --> 00:24:57.810
and they blew up, number
one in China immediately.

00:24:57.810 --> 00:24:59.400
And here I am
like, we're looking

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:01.660
like there's nothing we can do.

00:25:01.660 --> 00:25:03.460
Because we had not
launched in China.

00:25:03.460 --> 00:25:04.560
We weren't ready for it.

00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:06.980
They got a huge head start.

00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:10.390
And that was really, really
nerve racking and scary.

00:25:10.390 --> 00:25:13.210
But you have to
focus on building

00:25:13.210 --> 00:25:14.590
one product for the world.

00:25:14.590 --> 00:25:15.798
And that's what we had to do.

00:25:15.798 --> 00:25:17.430
We just don't let
it get to us, focus

00:25:17.430 --> 00:25:19.044
on building this one product.

00:25:19.044 --> 00:25:21.210
the meantime, we built a--
we formed a joint venture

00:25:21.210 --> 00:25:22.620
in China.

00:25:22.620 --> 00:25:26.730
We found a local team in China
to build our version of Secret,

00:25:26.730 --> 00:25:29.120
to take and rebuild it.

00:25:29.120 --> 00:25:32.092
launched about a week ago,
and as of two days ago,

00:25:32.092 --> 00:25:33.550
became number one
in the App Store.

00:25:33.550 --> 00:25:36.550
So you just, you gotta
stop and-- thank you.

00:25:36.550 --> 00:25:37.870
Thank you.

00:25:37.870 --> 00:25:41.020
You gotta just step
back and focus on

00:25:41.020 --> 00:25:43.730
keep what you're doing.

00:25:43.730 --> 00:25:45.770
There are clones
in China, or sorry,

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:49.360
in India, Indonesia,
and other places.

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:51.350
But we were there first.

00:25:51.350 --> 00:25:53.045
And we got a-- we're
the innovators.

